d that these constitute a very real knowledge—a knowledge of the limits of what can be known. Establishing this “negative certainty,” Marion applies it to four aporias, or issues of certain uncertainty: the definition of man; the nature of God; the unconditionality of the gift; and the unpredictability of events. Translated for the first time into English, Negative Certainties is an invigorating work of epistemological inquiry that will take a central place in Marion’s oeuvre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCertainty. 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aNegative theology. 0aPhenomenology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aphilosophy, philosopher, philosophical, academic, scholarly, research, contemporary, modern, 20th century, knowledge, learning, intellectual, education, educational, college, university, higher ed, textbook, categorical, categories, predictive, predictions, positive, controversial, rational, limits, limitations, phenomenology, theology, god, religion, faith, belief, incomprehensible, paradox.1 aLewis, Stephen E.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226807102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226807102/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles